passages.text: Data center switches riding on China's cloud capex growth; TP raised to Rmb134; Buy
301165.SZ 12m Price Target: Rmb134.00 Price: Rmb103.61 Upside: \(29.3\%\)

We reiterate Buy on Ruijie Networks as we see (1) rising China Cloud capex (GSE BABA Capex in FY2026- 28E lifted post 1QFY26 result) to drive switch demand, (2) positive 2H25 outlook with strong visibility into data center switch growth, (3) migration to 400G/800G switches for data center high- speed transmission, and (4) accumulated experience in offering customized white- box solutions for major China CSP clients. We are positive on Ruijie as a local switch leader to ride on the Gen- AI trend in China and benefit from clients' migration to local supply chains to mitigate any geopolitical uncertainties. Maintain Buy with a revised TP of Rmb134 (vs. prior Rmb103.1). Read more: Ruijie initiation; Global Switch TAM.

Data center switches riding on China's Cloud Capex: BABA reported 1QFY26 Capex spending \(+57\%\) QoQ to Rmb39bn, supported by its multi- chip approach, and our analyst Ronald Keung raised BABA FY26E- FY28E capex to Rmb350bn (vs. previously at Rmb290bn, Report link), which is positive for Ruijie (BABA is Ruijie's largest customer in data center switch). Ruijie is positive on data center switch growth in 2H25E, driven by the rising AI infrastructure demand and migration to local AI chipset with a local ecosystem. We expect Ruijie's market share as the local data center switch leader to grow from \(3\%\) in 2024 to \(5\%\) / \(10\%\) in 2025/30E, supported by its white- box solution to fulfill different clients' needs.

Earnings revision: We raise earnings by \(2\% /13\% /14\%\) in 2025- 27E mainlyon higher revenue from data center and SMB switches, and lower Opex ratio. We revise our revenue estimates mainly on data center switch growth driven by strong demand and mix upgrade towards 400G/800G solution and SMB switch riding on overseas market growth. GS estimates vs. BBG consensus: Our NI is \(6\% /23\%\) higher than Bloomberg consensus in 2025/26E, mainly on higher revenues, lower GM, and lower Opex ratios. The higher revenues reflect our positive view on Ruijie's market leading position in data center switches, riding on China's Cloud capex upward trend. The lower GM is due to higher revenue contribution from data center white box solution carrying lower margins. The lower Opex ratio is driven by higher revenue scales and higher operational efficiency.

Valuation: We continue to use a near- term P/E to derive our 12M target price. We update our target multiple to 72.4x 2026E EPS (vs. 63.1x 2026E EPS previously), which is derived from peer correlation of 2026E P/E to 2026- 27E avg. EPS YoY. Our 2026- 27E EPS estimates have increased from 34% YoY to 42% YoY. With our updated target P/E and earnings, we increase our 12M TP to Rmb134.0 (vs. Rmb103.1 previously). Our target P/E implied PEG&M is at 1.3x (target P/E multiple to forward year NI YoY and OPM), while peers are in the range 0.6x to 1.5x PEG&M. Our implied PEG&M is higher than peers on average, reflecting Ruijie's leading position in China's switch market and its accumulated experience in customized products. Our target PE multiple of 72.4x is at the high end of the company's historical trading range, while our TP implied 29x 2030E PE (vs. 20% NI YoY in 2030E) lies in between the company's avg. PE (34x) and avg.- 1stv. PE (23x). Maintain Buy.

Discounted P/E valuation cross- check: We adopt a discounted P/E methodology for cross- check (Exhibit 9) with base year at 2028E EPS, when forward year earnings growth normalized to \(20 - 30\%\) YoY post the strong ramp up in 2025- 27E on China AI infrastructure cycle. We apply a 55.0x target PE on Ruijie's 2028E EPS, discounting back to 2026E at a COE of \(11.5\%\) (Beta 1.5x, risk free rate \(1.8\%\) and market risk premium at \(6.5\%\) ), resulting in an implied value per share at Rmb135.0. The target PE is based on the same PEG&M ratio as peers in the photonics supply chain (Exhibit 8). The peers' current trading 2026E P/E multiple implies 1.5x ratio to 2027 NI YoY growth and 2027 OPM; with Ruijie's 2029 NI growing at \(27\%\) YoY and OPM at \(9\%\) , we derive 55x target P/E on 2028E EPS.

What's priced in: We initiated coverage on Ruijie on August 14 (link). Over the last month, share price has increased by \(45\%\) with consensus (Bloomberg) revising up net income estimates \((+20\% /8\%\) in 2025/26E). We raise our \(2\% /14\%\) net income in 2025/26E. Our 2025/26E net income estimates are \(6\% /23\%\) higher than Bloomberg. We believe the positive catalysts from China Cloud investments in AI are being priced in, however, current market debates include: (1) the sustainability of Cloud Capex or AI inference demand in China, (2) the migration pace toward 800G/1.6T specifications in China's AI infrastructure, noting chipset performance gaps vs. US Cloud providers, and (3) competition - whether strong market demand would attract numerous entrants leading to fierce pricing competition, or CSP clients lowering the ASP to reduce costs in AI infrastructure. We believe the growing AI applications and improving functions will drive productivity and efficiency, hence driving market confidence in the AI supply chain in China.

Valuation: We derive our 12M TP of Rmb134.0 based on a target P/E multiple of 72.4x 2026E EPS. Our target P/E of 72.4x is derived from the correlation between P/E and EPS growth of Ruijie's peers, based on Ruijie's 2026- 27E EPS YoY growth.
Key risks: Slower- than- expected China Cloud capex expansion; Lower- than- expected demand for high- speed switch; Fi ercer- than- expected pricing competition

The Goldman Sachs Factor Profile provides investment context for a stock by comparing key attributes to the market (i.e. our universe of rated stocks) and its sector peers. The four key attributes depicted are: Growth, Financial Returns, Multiple (e.g. valuation) and Integrated (a composite of Growth, Financial Returns and Multiple). Growth, Financial Returns and Multiple are calculated by using normalized ranks for specific metrics for each stock. The normalized ranks for the metrics are then averaged and converted into percentiles for the relevant attribute. The precise calculation of each metric may vary depending on the fiscal year, industry and region, but the standard approach is as follows:

Growth is based on a stock's forward- looking sales growth, EBITDA growth and EPS growth (for financial stocks, only EPS and sales growth), with a higher percentile indicating a higher growth company. Financial Returns is based on a stock's forward- looking ROE, ROCE and CROCI (for financial stocks, only ROE), with a higher percentile indicating a company with higher financial returns. Multiple is based on a stock's forward- looking P/E, P/B, price/dividend (P/D), EV/EBITDA, EV/FCF and EV/Debt Adjusted Cash Flow (DACF) (for financial stocks, only P/E, P/B and P/D), with a higher percentile indicating a stock trading at a higher multiple. The Integrated percentile is calculated as the average of the Growth percentile, Financial Returns percentile and (100% - Multiple percentile).

Financial Returns and Multiple use the Goldman Sachs analyst forecasts at the fiscal year- end at least three quarters in the future. Growth uses inputs for the fiscal year at least seven quarters in the future compared with the year at least three quarters in the future (on a per- share basis for all metrics).
For a more detailed description of how we calculate the GS Factor Profile, please contact your GS representative.

Across our global coverage, we examine stocks using an M&A framework, considering both qualitative factors and quantitative factors (which may vary across sectors and regions) to incorporate the potential that certain companies could be acquired. We then assign a M&A rank as a means of scoring companies under our rated coverage from 1 to 3, with 1 representing high (30%- 50%) probability of the company becoming an acquisition target, 2 representing medium (15%- 30%) probability and 3 representing low (0%- 15%) probability. For companies ranked 1 or 2, in line with our standard departmental guidelines we incorporate an M&A component into our target price. M&A rank of 3 is considered immaterial and therefore does not factor into our price target, and may or may not be discussed in research.
